Five Below Inc (FIVE.0) From To Price Target \(\) 135.00\(\) 160.00\$

Solid merchandise and in- store execution continue with room for upside to 2H25e comps. That said, dynamic tariff landscape presents margin headwinds which will likely build into '26e, limiting EBIT/EPS growth.

How do Q2'25 results shape our view? We are Equal- weight rated. Risk/reward is balanced with \(\sim 40\%\) upside/downside to our bull/bear cases and \(\sim 9\%\) upside to our raised \(\) 160\(PT. FIVE continues to benefit from its improved execution in product, value offerings, and customer experiences, alongside reduced competition in the digital channel and competitor closures. This leaves room for comp upside in 2H25e, although tariff headwinds will weigh on profitability over the coming months and into '26e. Q2'25 comps were \(+12.4\%\) vs. the Street at \(8\%\) and EBIT/EPS of \(\) 55m\(\) \ \(0.81\) beat by \(\sim 30\%\) . This is also reflected in the Q3 comp guide of \(5 - 7\%\) (vs. Street at \(2\%\) ) and raised F25 comp expectations (to \(6\%\) at the midpoint vs. \(4\%\) prior). We think there is upside to 2H25 comps, given Q4 is implied to be \\~low- single- digits (vs. \(\sim 8.5\%\) on average in Q1- Q3), as drivers of this comp strength should continue.

'26 earnings power is the next critical juncture of this story, given harder y/y compares, potential tariff pressures, and the lapping of competitor closures. We currently forecast '26 comps of \(3\%\) , though we have low conviction in our estimate. This comp forecast would limit EBIT margin expansion to \(+15\) bps y/y \((\sim 8\%\) vs. \(\sim 7.9\%\) in '25e), putting EPS at \(\sim\) 5.65, or mid- teens % growth y/y - well below FIVE's '15- 19 average of \(\sim 29\%\) y/y. With current valuation re- rated to \(\sim 28x\) NTM P/E, almost at the 5- year average of \(\sim 30\%\) NTM P/E, we think below- average EPS growth in '26e would slow the stock's ascent. Conversely, risks to the upside include further share gains from merchandise and existing execution and sustained momentum in customer engagement.

1) Room for upside to 2H25e comps. The Q3/Q4 comp guidance for \(\sim 5 - 7\% / \sim\) low- single-digits, respectively, likely embeds a measure of conservatism. As FIVE continues to benefit from improved merchandising execution, marketing, better in- store experience, and competitor closures, we think there could be upside to 2H25e comps. In addition, unit degradation levels appear to be better vs. expectations, indicating no incremental weakness in consumer spending at FIVE for now.

2) Tariff pressures an overhang. The majority of tariff pressures are expected to come later into '25e, and more specifically in Q4, resulting in a \(\sim 275\) bps y/y EBIT margin decline on average in 2H25e. While '25e EBIT margin guidance was raised to

How our numbers are changing. We are raising our PT to \(\) 160\(from\) \ \(135\) based on \(\sim 25x\) our '27 EPS of \(\) 6.45\(vs. \sim 26x\) 26 EPS prior). We are rolling forward our valuation to '27 EPS estimates, but maintaining our underlying methodology. Our '25/26/27 EPS estimates are increasing by \(8\% /8\% /9\%\) . In '25, we model \(+6\%\) comps, gross margin contraction of \(\sim 75\) bps, and SGA deleverage of \(\sim 60\) bps, yielding an EBIT margin of \(\sim 7.9\%\) and EPS of \(\) 4.93\(. In '26/27, we model a +3\% / + 3.5\%\) comp, \(\sim 8.1\% / \sim 8.3\%\) in EBIT margin, and \(\) 5.66/\(\) 6.45\(in EPS. Our \sim 25x target multiple is in line with FIVE's long - term FY3 average. We think multiple expansion is limited from here given the current tariff dynamic, harder compares, and low visibility on the sustainability of top - line momentum post execution plans.

Top line: high teens unit growth with \(\sim 90\%\) new store productivity and low- to mid- single- digit comps driving high teens sales growth High teens EBIT & EPS growth, driven by stable to modestly expanding operating margins
